Reference - Authors: S Huet; D F Nixon; J B Rothbard; A Townsend; S A Ellis; A J McMichael
Reference - Title: Structural homologies between two HLA B27-restricted peptides suggest residues important for interaction with HLA B27.
Epitope - Comments: No strain was specified, so a representative Swiss-Prot entry with matching sequence was chosen.
Assay - Comments: The positively charged N-terminal lysine of gag265-276 (KRWIILGLNKIV) is essential for binding to HLA-B27 because its removal eliminated binding. When the tryptophan at position 3 is replaced by leucine or tyrosine, binding to HLA-B27 was increased in a competition assay using influenza-specific CTL, but the modified peptides were not recognized by HIV-specific CTL suggesting that the tryptophan may also interact with the T cell receptor.

Reference - Authors: M Ostankovitch; G Guichard; F Connan; S Muller; A Chaboissier; J Hoebeke; J Choppin; J P Briand; J G Guillet
Reference - Title: A partially modified retro-inverso pseudopeptide modulates the cytokine profile of CTL specific for an influenza virus epitope.
Epitope - Comments: Peptide Pol476-484 was identified and characterized previously.
Assay - Comments: Arbitrary units. The capacity of peptide Pol 476-484 to promote HLA-A2 assembly, and the subsequent stabilization of peptide-MHC complex was measured using an antibody specific for HLA-A2. Peptide Pol 476-484 promoted HLA-peptide complex formation to a degree similar to that of the wild-type M58-66 peptide, and the two variant analog peptides. However, this peptide was less capable of conferring HLA-peptide stabilization than either variant (Leu59 or PMRI), but was only slightly less capable than the wild-type peptide.

Reference - Title: A sequence pattern for peptides presented to cytotoxic T lymphocytes by HLA B8 revealed by analysis of epitopes and eluted peptides.
Epitope - Comments: The GAG 24-32 sequence is identical in many HIV-1 isolates.
Assay - Comments: The HIV-1 GAG 24-32 (p17.3a) peptide was tested for its ability to inhibit presentation of the HLA-B8-restricted NP 380-388 epitope to CTL specific for the NP 380-388 epitope.

Reference - Authors: J Sutton; S Rowland-Jones; W Rosenberg; D Nixon; F Gotch; X M Gao; N Murray; A Spoonas; P Driscoll; M Smith
Reference - Title: A sequence pattern for peptides presented to cytotoxic T lymphocytes by HLA B8 revealed by analysis of epitopes and eluted peptides.
Epitope - Comments: The GAG 261-269 peptide was chosen from the larger known HLA-B8-restricted GAG 255-269 epitope based on a motif generated from peptides eluted from HLA-B8 molecules. The GAG 261-269 sequence is identical in many HIV-1 isolates and corresponds to residues 259-267 of Swiss Prot ID P04591.
Assay - Comments: The HIV-1 GAG 261-269 (p24.13) peptide was tested for its ability to inhibit presentation of the HLA-B8-restricted NP 380-388 epitope to CTL specific for the NP 380-388 epitope.

Assay - Comments: The HIV-1 GAG 261-269 (p24.13) peptide was tested for its ability to inhibit presentation of the HLA-B8-restricted NP 380-388 epitope to CTL specific for the NP 380-388 epitope.

Reference - Title: A peptide-binding assay for the disease-associated HLA-DQ8 molecule.

Assay - Comments: The epitope inhibited antigen presentation of a well-characterized DQ8 binder peptide Ha.255-271(Y).

Reference - Title: Simultaneous prediction of binding capacity for multiple molecules of the HLA B44 supertype.

Reference - Authors: Lenong Li; Marlene Bouvier
Reference - Title: Structures of HLA-A*1101 complexed with immunodominant nonamer and decamer HIV-1 epitopes clearly reveal the presence of a middle, secondary anchor residue.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Tables I, II, Figures 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 and PDB 1Q94
Assay - Comments: There are two molecules in the crystallographic asymmetric unit. PDB chains for each complex are: Complex 1': MHC α-chain: A, β2-m chain: B, epitope chain: C. Complex 2': MHC α-chain: D, β2-m chain: E, epitope chain: F. Electron density for the entire peptide in both molecules was well resolved. Main chain conformations of the two molecules are essentially identical, but the side chain of P1 is rotated. Also, the side chains of residues P4, P6 and P7 adopt slightly different orientations in the two molecules.

Reference - Authors: Lenong Li; Marlene Bouvier
Reference - Title: Structures of HLA-A*1101 complexed with immunodominant nonamer and decamer HIV-1 epitopes clearly reveal the presence of a middle, secondary anchor residue.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Tables I, II, Figures 2, 3, 4, 6 and PDB 1QVO
Assay - Comments: There are two molecules in the crystallographic asymmetric unit. PDB chains for each complex are: Complex 1: MHC α-chain: A, β2-m chain: B, epitope chain: C. Complex 2: MHC α-chain: D, β2-m chain: E, epitope chain: F. Electron density for the entire peptide in both molecules was continuous and clearly visible. Although main chain conformations of the two molecules are essentially identical, side chains of P4, P5, P7 and P8 show slightly different orientations. Specifically, the re-orientation of the P7Side chain is due to a change in the conformation of the MHC residue A: Q156.

Reference - Title: Large scale analysis of peptide-HLA class I interactions
Assay - Comments: In general, this data has been generated using a quantitative biochemical peptide-HLA interaction assay (see PMID: 12135423). The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

Assay - Comments: In general, this data has been generated using a quantitative biochemical peptide-HLA interaction assay (see PMID: 12135423). The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

Epitope - Source Molecule: Chain A, Structure Of The N-Terminal 283-Residue Fragment Of The Hiv- 1 Gag Polyprotein
Assay - Comments: In general, this data has been generated using a quantitative biochemical peptide-HLA interaction assay (see PMID: 12135423). The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

The HLA class I molecules have been selected to cover the known HLA supertypes (using PMID: 14963618). Predictions of peptide binding to HLA class I has been performed using various bioinformatics approaches including artificial neural networks (see PMID: 14617044 �and PMID: 12717023 peptides and using a combined algorithm integrating MHC class I binding, TAP transport efficiency, and proteasomal cleavage predictions (PMID: 15997466). In many cases, the most informative peptides have been selected using a Query-by-Committeee procedure (using PMID: 14617044 and PMID: 14629874).

Reference - Authors: Michael Rasmussen M.Sc.; Mikkel Nors Harndahl Ph.D.; Lise Lotte Nielsen M.Sc.; Anette Stryhn Ph.D.; Morten Nielsen Ph.D.; Sören Buus MD, Ph.D.
Reference - Title: Describing the peptide binding specificity of HLA-C molecules
Assay - Comments: Peptide-HLA-I (pHLA-I) complexes were formed by refolding of recombinant, biotinylated HLA-I molecules in the presence of increasing concentrations of peptide. pHLA-I complexes were detected, via formation of a conformational epitope recogniced by the W6/32 pan-specific MHC-I antibody, using a proximity based Luminescence Oxygen Channeling Immunoassay (LOCI). The signal obtained was converted into nM MHC-I complex using a prefolded pHLA-A*02:01 standard. The concentration needed for half-saturation of MHC-I (the EC50) was calculated by non-linear regression. At low concentrations of receptor (i.e. receptor concentration < equilibrium dissociation constant observed), the EC50 is an approximation of the true equilibrium dissociation constant.

Reference - Title: Describing the peptide binding specificity of HLA-C molecules
Assay - Comments: Peptide-HLA-I (pHLA-I) complexes were formed by refolding of recombinant, biotinylated HLA-I molecules in the presence of increasing concentrations of peptide. pHLA-I complexes were detected, via the formation of a conformational epitope recognized by the W6/32 pan-specific MHC-I antibody, using a proximity based Luminescence Oxygen Channeling Immunoassay (LOCI). The signal obtained was converted into nM MHC-I complex using a prefolded pHLA-A*02:01 standard. The concentration needed for half-saturation of MHC-I (the EC50) was calculated by non-linear regression. At low concentrations of receptor (i.e. receptor concentration < equilibrium dissociation constant observed), the EC50 is an approximation of the true equilibrium dissociation constant.

Reference - Authors: Cristina Maria Costantino; Eric Spooner; Hidde L Ploegh; David A Hafler
Reference - Title: Class II MHC self-antigen presentation in human B and T lymphocytes.
Antigen Processing - Comments: T cell clones were generated from the peripheral blood of two healthy individuals. CD4 T cells were isolated from whole blood using the CD4+ T cell negative isolation kit II (Miltenyi Biotech) and sorted at one cell per well into plates containing irradiated PBMC, recombinant Il-2, anti-CD3 and anti-CD28. Clones were expanded for 4 weeks and then subsequently re-stimulated with anti- CD3 and CD28. Peptides were eluted from affinity-purified HLA-DR molecules (L243) and sequence analysis was performed using liquid chromatography and nano-electrospray ionization tandem mass spectrometry.
MHC Restriction - Evidence Code: Elution with MHC specific antibody - Tu36

Reference - Title: Effects of Cross-Presentation, Antigen Processing, and Peptide Binding in HIV Evasion of T Cell Immunity.
Assay - Comments: The epitope stabilized the expression of H-2Dd on RMA-S cells. Comparing peptides with Thr at the penultimate position, the following hierarchy of binding was observed: s.p.TI10 > s.p.TV10 > s.p.TT10, demonstrating that the more hydrophobic anchor residues, Ile and Val, enhance the interaction of the peptide with H2-Dd more than does the less hydrophobic Thr residue. Keeping the anchor residue constant and comparing the penultimate position between Thr and Val, Thr always bound with greater affinity to H2-Dd: s.p.TI10 > s.p.VI10, s.p.TV10 > s.p.VV10, and s.p.TT10 > s.p.VT10.

Reference - Title: Primary and secondary functions of HLA-E are determined by stability and conformation of the peptide-bound complexes.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Figures 1, 3, Supplementary Figures S1, S3 and Table 1
Assay - Comments: Peptide exchange reactions were conducted using HLA-E*01:03-ß2m complexes pre-refolded with a UV-sensitive VL9 variant (VMAPJTVLL) and analyzed by Blue native gel electrophoesis and by sandwich ELISA. Analysis of the epitope/HLA-E complex by size exclusion chromatography-coupled small-angle X-ray scattering (SEC-SAXS) revealed that RL9HIV-refolded HLA-E did not show a uniformly compact, fully folded HLA-E complex form in solution unless molar excess peptide was added to the HPLC elution buffer.

Reference - Title: Primary and secondary functions of HLA-E are determined by stability and conformation of the peptide-bound complexes.
Assay - Comments: The thermal stability of the epitope/ HLA-E*01:03 complex was determined by differential scanning ﬂuorimetry (DSF) methodology measured in the presence of 12 M excess peptide.

Reference - Authors: Kenji Murata; Dalam Ly; Hiroshi Saijo; Yukiko Matsunaga; Kenji Sugata; Fumie Ihara; Daisuke Oryoji; Yota Ohashi; Kayoko Saso; Chung-Hsi Wang; Evey Y F Zheng; Brian D Burt; Marcus O Butler; Naoto Hirano
Reference - Title: Modification of the HLA-A*24:02 Peptide Binding Pocket Enhances Cognate Peptide-Binding Capacity and Antigen-Specific T Cell Activation.
Assay - Comments: Epitope-MHC binding was assessed by flow cytometry of T2 cells transduced with wildtype HLA-A*24:02 or mutated A24:02 (A81L, L82R, or R83G).  Binding of the epitope was enhanced by the A81L mutation, whereas the L82R or R83G mutations had either no effect or reduced/inhibited MHC binding of the epitope.
